1. URI Versioning (/v1/resource)

When to Use:

You're building a public API or RESTful service.

You want to make versioning explicit and easily cacheable.

Clients are third-party consumers who need clarity in the API lifecycle.

Pros:

Simple and clear.

Easy to document and test.

Caches well.

Cons:

Breaks REST principles (URI should identify a resource, not a version).

You may need to duplicate routing logic for different versions.

Real-World Example:
GitHub API
https://api.github.com/v3/repos


2. Request Parameter Versioning (/resource?version=1)
When to Use:

You want a lightweight, simple form of versioning.

The version may be optional or configurable dynamically.

Works well for internal services or when versioning isn't the primary concern.

Pros:

Simple to implement.

Less invasive than URI versioning.

Cons:

Not ideal for caching (URLs look similar).

Can get messy with many parameters.

Real-World Example:

Lightweight internal APIs.

Feature flags in internal dev environments.


3. Header Versioning (e.g., X-API-VERSION)
  
When to Use:

You want clean URLs without version clutter.

You control the clients (e.g., mobile app and backend both owned by you).

Your system supports advanced header parsing.

Pros:

Keeps URI clean.

Supports more RESTful design.

Cons:

Not easily visible (e.g., in browser or URL sharing).

Harder to test with tools like curl or Postman.

Not cache-friendly.

Real-World Example:

Microsoft Azure APIs or Amazon AWS services often support custom header-based versioning.

4. Media Type Versioning (Accept Header / Content Negotiation)
When to Use:

You want fine-grained control over response formats.

Your API supports multiple representations (e.g., JSON, XML, HAL, etc.).

You want to follow a RESTful and HATEOAS-oriented approach.

Pros:

RESTful.

Good for clients that rely on content negotiation.

Useful for versioning content types and schemas.

Cons:

Complexity increases.

Not intuitive for many developers.

Difficult debugging and testing.

Real-World Example:

GitHub again:
Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json


Recommendation Summary                     Situation	Recommended Versioning
Public API with many consumers	                  URI versioning
Internal service with stable consumers	          Request parameter
Same URL with multiple representations	          Media type (Accept)
Clean URL & full client control	                  Header versioning
  
  

  
  
